<HEADLINE>
<P>
VERNAL EQUINOX 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
As I drove down Magnolia Boulevard in Sherman Oaks the other day, I observed a 
very comforting sight even though it nearly blinded me. The time was 6:03 p.m. 
and I was driving due west as the sun was just sinking below the horizon. 
</P>
<P>
The awe I felt was in part due to the recognition of the event that I observed. 
It was nature proclaiming the Vernal Equinox as it has recurred for the 
umpteenth time with precision and beauty. 
</P>
<P>
In the scheme of things, this event appeared to have gone unnoticed. I did not 
see it noted in newspaper editorials or in TV or radio commentary, but in this 
world of ours with its arbitrary standards and relative criteria there is a 
certain joy to behold in the simple truths of nature. It is an event that 
demonstrates order in an often chaotic surrounding. It is a discovery that 
belongs to children, or perhaps the child within us. 
</P>
<P>
ALLEN HANS 
</P>
<P>
Van Nuys 
</P>
</TEXT>
