</P>
</LENGTH>
<HEADLINE>
<P>
ARMENIA COMMUNIST PARTY CHIEF REPLACED 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By Times Staff Writer 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
<P>
MOSCOW 
</P>
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The leader of the Armenian Communist Party was replaced on Friday by a 
subordinate after two years of unremitting turmoil in the southern Soviet 
republic. 
</P>
<P>
Suren G. Arutyunyan, who had been named the Armenian party's first secretary in 
May, 1988, after months of strife with neighboring Azerbaijan, is succeeded by 
Vladimir M. Movsisyan, who had been chairman of the republic's agro-industrial 
commission and a first deputy prime minister. 
</P>
<P>
The official news agency Tass said that Arutyunyan, 51, a veterinarian who has 
worked as a party official for nearly 30 years, had sought a transfer to other 
unspecified duties. While Tass gave no explanation for the abrupt change, which 
was made by the Armenian party's Central Committee, Arutyunyan was regarded 
both in Moscow and in Armenia as less and less effective in dealing with the 
growing nationalism there. 
</P>
</TEXT>
