April 7, 1990, Saturday, Home Edition 
</P>
</DATE>
<SECTION>
<P>
Business; Part D; Page 2; Column 1; Financial Desk 
</P>
</SECTION>
<LENGTH>
<P>
112 words 
</P>
</LENGTH>
<HEADLINE>
<P>
BRIEFLY 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
From Times Staff and Wire Service Reports 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Browning-Ferris Taking $295-Million Charge: Browning-Ferris Industries Inc., a 
waste disposal giant, announced that it is getting out of the hazardous-waste 
business and taking a $295-million charge against earnings in the second 
quarter. 
</P>
<P>
Hazardous-waste business added 2% to the Houston-based company's revenue but 
reduced earnings by 10% and accounted for "75% of our headaches," John Stanton, 
Browning-Ferris' chief financial officer said. The hazardous-waste collection, 
treatment and disposal businesses have lost money for a year and a half. The 
firm said it will operate the hazardous-waste business until it is sold or 
converted to non-hazardous uses. 
</P>
</TEXT>
<TYPE>
<P>
Column; Brief; Corporate Earnings 
</P>
</TYPE>
<SUBJECT>
<P>
BROWNING FERRIS INDUSTRIES INC; HAZARDOUS MATERIALS -- DISPOSAL; RUBBISH 
COLLECTION; CORPORATE RESTRUCTURING 
</P>
</SUBJECT>
